Many identities involving binomial coefficients can be proved by combinatorial means. For example, for nonnegative integers formula_71, the identity
(which reduces to () when "q" = 1) can be given a double counting proof, as follows. The left side counts the number of ways of selecting a subset of ["n"] = {1, 2, ..., "n"} with at least "q" elements, and marking "q" elements among those selected. The right side counts the same thing, because there are formula_73 ways of choosing a set of "q" elements to mark, and formula_74 to choose which of the remaining elements of ["n"] also belong to the subset.
In Pascal's identity
both sides count the number of "k"-element subsets of ["n"]: the two terms on the right side group them into those that contain element "n" and those that do not.
The identity () also has a combinatorial proof. The identity reads
